class Solution {
    public int nthUglyNumber(int n) {
        int[] ugly = new int[n];
        ugly[0] = 1;
        int i2 = 0, i3 = 0, i5 = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            int next2 = 2 * ugly[i2], next3 = 3 * ugly[i3], next5 = 5 * ugly[i5];
            int nextUgly = Math.min(next2, Math.min(next3, next5));
            ugly[i] = nextUgly;
            if (nextUgly == next2) i2++;
            if (nextUgly == next3) i3++;
            if (nextUgly == next5) i5++;
        }
        return ugly[n - 1];
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses dynamic programming to generate the sequence of ugly numbers, maintaining pointers for the next multiples of 2, 3, and 5, and selecting the smallest to ensure the sequence is generated in ascending order efficiently.
